2026-05-18 | Maximum Sum with Recursive Breaks

	Question
Return maximum possible value.
	Key Insight
For every number n:
		answer =
		max(
				n,
				f(n/2)+f(n/3)+f(n/4)
		)
This naturally forms:
		overlapping subproblems
So:
		use memoization DP.
	Approach
1.	Define recursive function solve(n)
2.	Base:
		if n == 0:
				return 0
3.	If already computed:
		return memoized value
4.	Compute:
		breakValue =
				solve(n/2)
			  + solve(n/3)
			  + solve(n/4)
5.	Return:
		max(n, breakValue)
	Time Complexity
	O(number of distinct states)
	Space Complexity
	O(number of states)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    unordered_map<long long, long long> dp;
    long long solve(long long n){
        if(n == 0)
            return 0;
        if(dp.count(n))
            return dp[n];
        long long breakValue =
            solve(n/2) +
            solve(n/3) +
            solve(n/4);
        return dp[n] = max(n, breakValue);
    }
    long long maxSum(long long n) {
        return solve(n);
    }
};
	Key Insight
Sometimes breaking gives better profit,
sometimes keeping original number is better.  
So for every state:
		choose maximum of:
				keep OR break recursively.
